### Bayesian method is better than non-Bayesian

As discussed in Section 5, we found that in practice _Soft Reset_ and _Soft Reset Proximal_ where \(\gamma\) is learned per-parameter, did not perform well on the plasticity benchmarks. However, the Bayesian variant described in Section E.1, actually benefited from specifying \(\gamma\) for every parameter in Neural Network. We report these additional results in Figure 20. We see that the non Bayesian variants where \(\gamma_{t}\) is specified per parameter, do not perform well. The fact that the Bayesian method performs better here suggests that it is important to have a good uncertainty estimate \(\sigma_{t}^{2}\) for the update (10) on \(\gamma_{t}\). When, however, we regularize \(\gamma_{t}\) to be shared across all parameters within each layer, this introduces useful inductive bias which mitigates the lack of uncertainty estimation in the parameters. This is because for non-Bayesian methods, we assume that the uncertainty is fixed, given by a hyperparameter - assumption which would not always hold in practice.

